From: F5OEO <evaristec@gmail.com>
Date: Thu, 18 Jun 2026
Subject: [PATCH] ws: fix missing blank-line terminator in HTTP 101 response

When a WebSocket upgrade is performed without negotiating a subprotocol
or extensions, the Sec-WebSocket-Accept header value is written with no
trailing CRLF.  The single \r\n at the end of the response builder
therefore terminates the Accept header line rather than acting as the
mandatory blank line that separates HTTP headers from the message body
(RFC 7230 §3).

Clients that follow RFC 7230 strictly (e.g. cpp-httplib) observe a
stream of the form:

  Sec-WebSocket-Accept: <value>\r\n<WS binary frame>

instead of the required:

  Sec-WebSocket-Accept: <value>\r\n\r\n<WS binary frame>

and reject the upgrade.

Fix by checking whether the last byte already ends a header line
(\x0a) before writing the blank-line terminator.  When a subprotocol
or extensions are present they each write their own trailing \r\n, so
the check is a no-op in those paths.

Signed-off-by: F5OEO <evaristec@gmail.com>
---
 lib/roles/ws/server-ws.c | 7 +++++++
 1 file changed, 7 insertions(+)

--- a/lib/roles/ws/server-ws.c
+++ b/lib/roles/ws/server-ws.c
@@ -765,6 +765,13 @@ lws_process_ws_upgrade2(struct lws *wsi)

 	/* end of response packet */

+	/* When no subprotocol or extensions are negotiated, the
+	 * Sec-WebSocket-Accept header has no trailing CRLF yet.
+	 * Ensure the last header line is terminated before the
+	 * mandatory blank line that ends the HTTP response header
+	 * section (RFC 7230 §3). */
+	if (p > response && p[-1] != '\x0a')
+		LWS_CPYAPP(p, "\x0d\x0a");
 	LWS_CPYAPP(p, "\x0d\x0a");

 	/* okay send the handshake response accepting the connection */
